subsubsection.p:
On the unit circle, the hypotenuse of this right triangle was always 1, but for (x,y) coordinates on a circle of radius r, the hypotenuse of the right triangle equals r. The Pythagorean Theorem tells us that the quantities x, y, and r are related via
\begin{equation}\label{eq:r-circle-formula}
x^2 + y^2 = r^2
\end{equation}

	The lighter red circle in Figure X is centered at the origin, so we know a formula for the points on this circle:
	\begin{equation}\label{eq:circle-origin-rad4}
  {\color{red} x^2 + y^2 = 16}
	\end{equation}

The blue circle in Figure X, the circle of radius 4 which is centered at the point (7,0), looks identical to the circle whose equation is given by \eqref{eq:circle-origin-rad4}, just shifted 7 units to the right. Our knowledge of transformations of functions tells us that their formulae look very similar, but to shift 7 units to the right, replace each variable "x" in the formula with "x-7", which gives the formula for the circle of radius 4 centered (7,0):
\begin{equation}\label{eq:circle-7_0-rad4}
{\color{blue} (x-7)^2 + y^2 = 16}
\end{equation}

subsection.p:
Because the formula for the unit circle is an implicit formula, we treat our vertical stretch similarly, accomplishing stretching the graph vertically by a factor of 3 by replacing each instance of "y" in the formula with "\frac{1}{3}y". Thus, the formula that represents the ellipse depicted in Figure X is given by:
\begin{equation}\label{eq:ellipse-origin-5_3}
\left( \frac{1}{5} x \right)^2 + \left( \frac{1}{3} y \right)^2 \amp= 1.
\end{equation}
Note the very careful use of parentheses. In the formula for the unit circle, x^2+y^2=1, each variable x and y is being squared. If we wish to replace, say, each instance of the variable x with the expression "\frac{1}{5}x", we must add parentheses to make sure that order of operations is followed appropriately (with \frac{1}{5} multiplying x first, then squaring the result).

Although formula \eqref{eq:ellipse-origin-5_3} perfectly captures the collection of all points that lie on the ellipse depicted in Figure X, it is helpful to do some algebra to obtain another presentation of the formula:
\begin{align*}
\left( \frac{1}{5} x \right)^2 + \left( \frac{1}{3} y \right)^2 \amp= 1 \\
\left( \frac{x}{5} \right)^2 + \left( \frac{y}{3} \right)^2 \amp= 1 \\
\frac{x^2}{5^2} + \frac{y^2}{3^2} \amp= 1
\end{align*}
